==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Protoplast
<hw>Pro"to*plast</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>protoplastus</ets> the first man, Gr. <?/ formed or created first;
<?/ first + <?/ formed, fr. <?/ to form.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>The thing first formed; that of which there are
subsequent copies or reproductions; the original.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>A first-formed organized body;
the first individual, or pair of individuals, of a species.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A species is a class of individuals, each of which is
hypothetically considered to be the descendant of the same
<qex>protoplast</qex>, or of the same pair of
<qex>protoplasts</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Latham.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- 3. a plant or bacterial cell which has lost its cell wall. As a
consequence, protoplasts typically assume a spherical shape, and are
unable to resist rupture in a liquid of low osmolarity; but they may
live and in some cases divide, provided that the osmotic pressure of the
medium is sufficient to prevent expansion to the point of rupture.
-->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Protoplasta</ent>⟦br⟧
